metadata.name: (un)existing #63
metadata.description:
The existing nature grows on the unexisting spirits.

Generative sketch, based on the pen and ink drawings of Po Sheng Chen. Po Sheng Chen is an Architect who has drawn nothing but Architecture for over 25 years. He tried to explore something different from his previous style (Brutalism with Magical Realism), so developed his own Minimalist Architecture process and style. After breaking up all the complicated elements and symbols, he chose a simple and naive way to present “pure volumes in the space (the essential of Architecture)”: the Use of different densities of vertical lines to create different faces of volumes, with the addition of horizontal lines to create shadows on the volumes. Shadow determined the form of volumes, then they became a clear composition in the space, Eliminating chaos. These lines seem like spirits to Po Sheng Chen, because they represent the soul of Architecture, but they do not have a specific form or meaning...they are between existing and unexisting! Tezumie is a creative generative artist. He saw the latest experimental drawings of Po Sheng Chen, and after reaching out, the collab was formed with the goal of creating a digital representation of the original concept surrounded by a natural and overgrown environment. The combination of nature and architecture.

Made in p5js.

metadata.name: Mur #246
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Sherwood #14
metadata.description:
In the forest, foggy, cloudy weather creates a mysterious, otherworldly atmosphere.

----

Controls:
s or [double click] - save
1 through 8 - set the pixel density for higher resolutions. Base is 2000x1000.
d - increase debug level (none, overlay, overlay + animated drawing)
D - decrease debug level
[plus] or [equal] - increase the edition of the mint (see a new location with the same features)
[minus] - decrease the edition, to a minimum of zero

Made with:
- p5js
- Simplex noise (hills, cleared/forested, grass height, tree size & separation)
- Poisson disk sampling (tree distribution)

metadata.name: miniGlyph #44
metadata.description:
In celebration of #tezos4tezos I am releasing this mini version of a more complex work in progress. 

Every 24th mint (ex: 1, 24, 48, 72, etc) will receive a free physical woodcut.
https://alleditions.art/p/miniglyph

This project is designed such that it can export a layered vector SVG that can be used for plotting or cutting out of wood with a laser or paper with a Cricut.

Shift P - Export a PNG
Shift S - Export an SVG
Shift E - explode the layers

metadata.name: Proxima #178
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: Syzers #102
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Mandatory Destiny #37
metadata.description:
"Mandatory Destiny" is the fifth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

It is impossible for everyone to be equal. Too much of a person is defined by random chance. The country they were born in, the financial situation of their family, even their genetics. If someone was unlucky and has low natural IQ, they can't change it. And it affects their life significantly. If someone was born in a poor country or family, it might be extremely harder to get a good education, and later, a well-paying job. Some people are fortunate enough to get a headstart, while others aren't so lucky.

The only way for everyone to be truly equal would be identical starting conditions, and that's utterly impossible to achieve.

metadata.name: Tangled #164
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Extreme Ways Sketchup #80
metadata.description:
« Extreme ways are back again..."

This artwork is proposed as a gift for all Extreme Ways owners (at mint time of Extreme Ways Sketchup).
Very few changes in the code with respect to Extreme Ways (mainly freezing or imposing strict limits to main parameters).

It can be viewed as a sketchup of the first steps of Extreme Ways.

Will you keep it ?
Will you sell it (and then earn 25% of royalties) ?
Will you try to get one that looks like your Extreme Ways to get a match ?
It's up to you...

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key ’s’  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution


For Extreme Ways, a guide for interactivity is available : 
https://sites.google.com/view/tidally-disrupted-star/extreme-ways/interactivity


Royalties.
First minter will get 25% of the Royalties.

metadata.name: Ignorance is Bliss #127
metadata.description:
"Ignorance is Bliss" is the second collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

People often argue over things that are not under their control. But why bother? At the end of the day, your opinion won't change anything unless you have the power to accomplish that change. Of course you can say that you are aguing for "The Truth" or "Justice", but what's the point in your bickering if you aren't going to accomplish anything?
But you can go even further than that, you can choose to ignore global problems completely, live in your own world. One who doesn't know of a problem shan't worry about it - thus, ignorance is bliss. 
Is it right or is it wrong? What's the point in arguing over what I wrote if you won't change anything? All you can do is decide for yourself.
